
[1]infancy

   IN'FANCY, n. [L. infantia. See Infant.]

   1. The first part of life, beginning at the birth. In common usage,
   infancy extends not beyond the first year or two of life, but there is
   not a defined limit where infancy ends, and childhood begins.

   2. In law, infancy extends to the age of twenty one years.

   3. The first age of any thing; the beginning or early period of
   existence; as the infancy of the Roman republic; the infancy of a
   college or of a charitable society; the infancy of agriculture, of
   manufactures, or of commerce.
